SIMPLE: scourge
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scourge
<hw>Scourge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>escourg⟦eacute⟧e</ets>, fr. L. <ets>excoriata</ets> (sc.
<ets>scutica</ets>) a stripped off (lash or whip), fr.
<ets>excoriare</ets> to strip, to skin. See <er>Excoriate</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A lash; a strap or cord; especially, a lash used to
inflict pain or punishment; an instrument of punishment or discipline; a
whip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Up to coach then goes⟦br⟧
The observed maid, takes both the <qex>scourge</qex> and reins.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a means of inflicting punishment, vengeance,
or suffering; an infliction of affliction; a punishment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sharp <qex>scourges</qex> of adversity.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>scourge</qex> for perjury⟦br⟧
Can this dark monarchy afford false Clarence?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scourge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scourge
<hw>Scourge</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scourged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scourging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From
<er>Scourge</er>, <pos>n.</pos>: cf. OF. <ets>escorgier</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To whip severely; to lash.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Is it lawful for you to <qex>scourge</qex> a . . . Roman?</q>
<rj><qau>Acts xxii. 25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To punish with severity; to chastise; to afflict, as
for sins or faults, and with the purpose of correction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whom the Lord loveth he chasteneth, and <qex>scourgeth</qex> every
son whom he receiveth.</q> <rj><qau>Heb. xii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To harass or afflict severely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>scourge</qex> and impoverish the people.</q>
<rj><qau>Brougham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scourger</ent>⟦br⟧
